  <div class="container">
    <!-- Page Title, Problem Description, and Symptoms -->
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-md-8 col-xl-6 text-center mx-auto">
        <!-- Title in one line -->
        <h1 class="display-4 fw-bold mb-4" style="line-height: 1.2; color: #260d5e;">
          How to Handle a Choking Incident Until Help Arrives
        </h1>
        <!-- Brief problem description -->
        <p class="lead text-muted">
          Quick, decisive action is critical when someone is choking.
        </p>
        <!-- Short symptoms section in red -->
        <p class="fs-5" style="color: red;">
          <strong>Symptoms:</strong> Inability to speak, difficulty breathing, and clutching the throat.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
    
    <!-- Main Content: Do's and What Not To Do -->
    <div class="row align-items-center">
      <!-- Left Column: Guidelines -->
      <div class="col-md-6">
        <h3 class="fw-bold mb-3">Immediate Steps (Do's):</h3>
        <ol class="fs-5">
          <li>
            <strong>Assess the Situation:</strong> Ask if the person can cough or speak.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Perform the Heimlich Maneuver:</strong> If they cannot cough, perform abdominal thrusts.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Encourage Coughing:</strong> If the person can cough, encourage them to continue.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Call Emergency Services:</strong> Dial your local emergency number immediately.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Monitor the Person:</strong> Keep a close watch on their condition until help arrives.
          </li>
        </ol>
        <h3 class="fw-bold mt-4 mb-3">What Not To Do:</h3>
        <ul class="fs-5">
          <li>Do not hit the person forcefully on the back.</li>
          <li>Avoid performing blind finger sweeps.</li>
          <li>Do not delay calling for help.</li>
          <li>Do not panic or let panic spread.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-muted mt-3">
          <em>Note:</em> This guide is for emergency use only and is not a substitute for professional medical training.
        </p>
      </div>
      
